from pyspark.sql import SparkSession

# Create Spark session
spark = SparkSession.builder \
    .appName("Crime Data Analysis") \
    .config("spark.hadoop.fs.defaultFS", "hdfs://localhost:9000") \
    .getOrCreate()

Reading Data¶

This document lists the Chicago crime data files uploaded to HDFS. Each file contains records of incidents reported to the Chicago Police Department.

Uploaded Files to HDFS¶

File Name Size (bytes) Last Modified
/data/Chicago_Crimes_2001_to_2004.csv 475,343,924 2024-10-20 12:21
/data/Chicago_Crimes_2005_to_2007.csv 471,278,284 2024-10-20 12:22
/data/Chicago_Crimes_2008_to_2011.csv 677,693,675 2024-10-20 12:22
/data/Chicago_Crimes_2012_to_2017.csv 366,804,568 2024-10-20 12:22

Description of Files¶

  • Chicago_Crimes_2001_to_2004.csv: Contains crime incident data from the years 2001 to 2004.
  • Chicago_Crimes_2005_to_2007.csv: Contains crime incident data from the years 2005 to 2007.
  • Chicago_Crimes_2008_to_2011.csv: Contains crime incident data from the years 2008 to 2011.
  • Chicago_Crimes_2012_to_2017.csv: Contains crime incident data from the years 2012 to 2017.

root
 |-- _c0: integer (nullable = true)
 |-- ID: integer (nullable = true)
 |-- Case Number: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Date: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Block: string (nullable = true)
 |-- IUCR: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Primary Type: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Description: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Location Description: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Arrest: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Domestic: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Beat: string (nullable = true)
 |-- District: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Ward: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Community Area: string (nullable = true)
 |-- FBI Code: string (nullable = true)
 |-- X Coordinate: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Y Coordinate: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Year: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Updated On: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Latitude: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Longitude: string (nullable = true)
 |-- Location: string (nullable = true)
  • ID: Unique identifier for the record.
  • Case Number: The Chicago Police Department RD Number (Records Division Number), which is unique to the incident.
  • Date: Date when the incident occurred; this is sometimes a best estimate.
  • Block: The partially redacted address where the incident occurred, placing it on the same block as the actual address.
  • IUCR: The Illinois Uniform Crime Reporting code. This is directly linked to the Primary Type and Description. See the list of IUCR codes at IUCR Codes.
  • Primary Type: The primary description of the IUCR code.
  • Description: The secondary description of the IUCR code, a subcategory of the primary description.
  • Location Description: Description of the location where the incident occurred.
  • Arrest: Indicates whether an arrest was made.
  • Domestic: Indicates whether the incident was domestic-related as defined by the Illinois Domestic Violence Act.
  • Beat: Indicates the beat where the incident occurred. A beat is the smallest police geographic area – each beat has a dedicated police beat car. Three to five beats make up a police sector, and three sectors make up a police district. The Chicago Police Department has 22 police districts. See the beats at Beats.
  • District: Indicates the police district where the incident occurred. See the districts at Districts.
  • Ward: The ward (City Council district) where the incident occurred. See the wards at Wards.
  • Community Area: Indicates the community area where the incident occurred. Chicago has 77 community areas. See the community areas at Community Areas.
  • FBI Code: Indicates the crime classification as outlined in the FBI's National Incident-Based Reporting System (NIBRS). See the Chicago Police Department listing of these classifications at FBI Code.
  • X Coordinate: The x coordinate of the location where the incident occurred in State Plane Illinois East NAD 1983 projection. This location is shifted from the actual location for partial redaction but falls on the same block.
  • Y Coordinate: The y coordinate of the location where the incident occurred in State Plane Illinois East NAD 1983 projection. This location is shifted from the actual location for partial redaction but falls on the same block.
  • Year: Year the incident occurred.
  • Updated On: Date and time the record was last updated.
  • Latitude: The latitude of the location where the incident occurred. This location is shifted from the actual location for partial redaction but falls on the same block.
  • Longitude: The longitude of the location where the incident occurred. This location is shifted from the actual location for partial redaction but falls on the same block.
  • Location: The location where the incident occurred in a format that allows for creation of maps and other geographic operations on this data portal. This location is shifted from the actual location for partial redaction but falls on the same block. on the same block.

The analysis of arrest data over the past 16 years reveals that while the overall number of arrests has fluctuated, the relative distance between arrest and non-arrest incidents has remained consistent. This suggests that the patterns of arrests have not significantly changed in relation to non-arrest situations, indicating that the factors influencing arrests may have remained stable over time. Thus, despite variations in total arrest figures, the underlying dynamics between arrest and non-arrest cases appear to be enduringly similar.

Clustering¶

In [41]:
# Convert Latitude and Longitude from String to Float
df = df.withColumn("Latitude", col("Latitude").cast("float"))
df = df.withColumn("Longitude", col("Longitude").cast("float"))

# Now, drop rows with null values again if any are introduced after conversion
df_features = df.select("Latitude", "Longitude").na.drop()

# Assemble features into a vector
vector_assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=["Latitude", "Longitude"], outputCol="features")
df_features_vector = vector_assembler.transform(df_features)

# Train the K-means model
kmeans = KMeans(k=6, seed=1)
model = kmeans.fit(df_features_vector)

# Get cluster predictions
df_clustered = model.transform(df_features_vector)

# Show the clustered data
df_clustered.show(5)

In [43]:
# Define the number of clusters
n_clusters = 5

# Empty list to store clustered data for each crime type
crime_clusters = []

# Loop through each unique 'Primary Type' in the PySpark DataFrame
for crime_type in df.select("Primary Type").distinct().collect():
    crime_type_value = crime_type[0]
    
    # Filter the DataFrame for the current crime type
    crime_df = df.filter(F.col("Primary Type") == crime_type_value)
    
    # Filter out rows with null values in 'Latitude' or 'Longitude'
    crime_df = crime_df.na.drop(subset=["Latitude", "Longitude"])
    
    # Convert 'Latitude' and 'Longitude' to a vector column
    vector_assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=["Latitude", "Longitude"], outputCol="features")
    crime_df_vector = vector_assembler.transform(crime_df)
    
    # Perform KMeans clustering
    kmeans = KMeans(k=n_clusters, seed=42, featuresCol="features", predictionCol="Cluster")
    model = kmeans.fit(crime_df_vector)
    
    # Add the cluster predictions to the DataFrame
    crime_df_clustered = model.transform(crime_df_vector).select("Latitude", "Longitude", "Primary Type", "Cluster")
    
    # Convert to Pandas for plotting
    crime_df_pandas = crime_df_clustered.toPandas()
    
    # Append the Pandas DataFrame to the list
    crime_clusters.append(crime_df_pandas)

# Concatenate all the Pandas DataFrames into one
clustered_df = pd.concat(crime_clusters)
In [44]:
# Filter the concatenated Pandas DataFrame based on the latitude and longitude range
filtered_df = clustered_df[(clustered_df['Latitude'] >= 40) & (clustered_df['Latitude'] <= 44) & 
                           (clustered_df['Longitude'] >= -88) & (clustered_df['Longitude'] <= -86)].copy()

# Plotting the clustered crime locations
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Use Seaborn to create a scatter plot, coloring by the cluster number
sns.scatterplot(data=filtered_df, x="Longitude", y="Latitude", hue="Cluster", palette="deep", s=10)

# Add title and labels
plt.title("Crime Locations Clustered by Crime Type")
plt.xlabel("Longitude")
plt.ylabel("Latitude")

# Show plot
plt.show()

# Index categorical columns for use in the decision tree, with handleInvalid set to "keep"
arrest_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol="Arrest", outputCol="label", handleInvalid="keep")
primary_type_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol="Primary Type", outputCol="primary_type_index", handleInvalid="keep")
location_desc_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol="Location Description", outputCol="location_desc_index", handleInvalid="keep")
domestic_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol="Domestic", outputCol="domestic_index", handleInvalid="keep")
fbi_code_indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol="FBI Code", outputCol="fbi_code_index", handleInvalid="keep")
In [88]:
# Assemble features into a single vector
assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=["primary_type_index", "location_desc_index", "domestic_index", 
                                       "Beat", "District", "Ward", "Community Area", 
                                       "fbi_code_index", "Year"], outputCol="features")

# Define the Decision Tree Classifier
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(featuresCol="features", labelCol="label",maxBins=180)

# Build the pipeline
pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[arrest_indexer, primary_type_indexer, location_desc_indexer, domestic_indexer, fbi_code_indexer, assembler, dt])

# Split data into training and test sets (80% train, 20% test)
train_data, test_data = df.randomSplit([0.8, 0.2])

# Train the model
model = pipeline.fit(train_data)

# Test the model
predictions = model.transform(test_data)

Finding out which Type of crimes leads to the most arrests¶

In [94]:
# Group by Primary Type and Arrest to calculate the total arrests for each crime type
arrest_stats = df.groupBy("Primary Type").agg(
    F.count("Arrest").alias("total_cases"),  # Total number of cases for each crime type
    F.sum(F.when(F.col("Arrest") == True, 1).otherwise(0)).alias("total_arrests")  # Count of True (arrests)
)

# Calculate the arrest rate for each crime type
arrest_stats = arrest_stats.withColumn("arrest_rate", F.col("total_arrests") / F.col("total_cases"))

# Sort by arrest rate in descending order to see which crime types lead to the most arrests
arrest_stats = arrest_stats.orderBy(F.col("arrest_rate").desc())

# Show the results
arrest_stats.show(truncate=False)
